<subSubSection pageId="49" pageNumber="50" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
This monospecific genus has several autapomorphies compared with other genera within the tribe. It is the only species that has large and very persistent imbricate floral bracts along the inflorescence enclosing the uniquely golden-yellow flowers. 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Serawaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Serawaia" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Serawaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only genus in Clade D that has prominent gibbosities below the stipules. Its nearest affinities lie with 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Endl., Gen. Pl. Suppl. 3: 104" authorityYear="1843" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Callerya" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Callerya" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Callerya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton, Mattapha, Sirich. &amp; Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton, Mattapha, Sirich. &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Kanburia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kanburia" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Kanburia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Elmer" authorityName="Elmer, Leafl. Philipp. Bot. 2: 689, 743" authorityYear="1910" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Whitfordiodendron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Whitfordiodendron" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Whitfordiodendron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which all have sericeous backs to their standard petals. The back of the standards of 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Serawaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Serawaia" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Serawaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are, however, pubescent but the hairs are not as long as those in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craib, Bull. Misc. Inform. Kew 1927 (9): 376" authorityYear="1927" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Afgekia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Afgekia" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Afgekia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the other member of Clade D. The wing petals, which are free from the keel, almost equal the length of the keel as in 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton, Mattapha, Sirich. &amp; Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton, Mattapha, Sirich. &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Kanburia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Kanburia" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Kanburia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Elmer" authorityName="Elmer, Leafl. Philipp. Bot. 2: 689, 743" authorityYear="1910" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Whitfordiodendron" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Whitfordiodendron" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Whitfordiodendron</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Craib, Bull. Misc. Inform. Kew 1927 (9): 376" authorityYear="1927" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Afgekia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Afgekia" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Afgekia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
which distinguishes these four genera readily from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Endl., Gen. Pl. Suppl. 3: 104" authorityYear="1843" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Callerya" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Callerya" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Callerya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
whose wings are shorter. The ovary in 
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Serawaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Serawaia" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Serawaia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is only sparsely hairy whereas in all four other genera within Clade D the ovaries are densely sericeous (see figs 4 and 5 in 
<bibRefCitation author="Schot, AM" journalOrPublisher="Blumea" pageId="76" pageNumber="77" pagination="1 - 40" refId="B91" refString="Schot, AM, 1994. A Revision of Callerya Endl. (including Padbruggea and Whitfordiodendron) (Papilionaceae: Millettieae). Blumea 39: 1 - 40" title="A Revision of Callerya Endl. (including Padbruggea and Whitfordiodendron) (Papilionaceae: Millettieae)." volume="39" year="1994">Schot (1994</bibRefCitation>
: 33, 34).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="49" pageNumber="50" type="type species">
<paragraph pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Type species.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
<taxonomicName authority="J.Compton &amp; B.D.Schrire, 2019" authorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" authorityYear="2019" baseAuthorityName="J. Compton &amp; Schrire" baseAuthorityYear="2019" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Fabaceae" genus="Serawaia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Serawaia strobilifera" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strobilifera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Serawaia strobilifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Schot) J.Compton &amp; Schrire ≡ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schott" authorityYear="1994" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Leguminosae" genus="Callerya" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Callerya strobilifera" order="Fabales" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="strobilifera">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Callerya strobilifera</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Schot.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="50" lastPageNumber="51" pageId="49" pageNumber="50" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Genus description.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="50" lastPageNumber="51" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">
Scandent twining vines scrambling up trees and along river banks to 8 m high. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Stems</emphasis>
very pale grey or white, terete, glabrous. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Leaves</emphasis>
with 5-7 leaflets, evergreen, glabrous, imparipinnate, rachis 7-20 cm long. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Stipules</emphasis>
5-8 mm long, linear, persistent, arising from above prominent gibbosities. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Stipels</emphasis>
3-4 mm long, linear, persistent. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Leaflets</emphasis>
4-14 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-7 cm, broadly or narrowly elliptic, glabrous on both surfaces, apex acuminate or cuspidate, margins entire, base rounded to subcordate. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Inflorescence</emphasis>
erect, sometimes leafy few-branched panicles 12-20 cm long, peduncle pale grey, glabrous. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Flowers</emphasis>
15-21 mm long, emerging from May to August. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Floral bracts</emphasis>
15-18 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
8-12 mm, persistent, with longitudinal parallel venation, overlapping flower buds in a strobilate inflorescence. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Bracteoles</emphasis>
6-7 mm long, at top of pedicel, linear, persistent. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Pedicels</emphasis>
4-6 mm long, glabrous. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Calyx</emphasis>
3-6 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-6 mm campanulate, oblique, pubescent externally, five lobed, teeth distinctly unequal 2-6 mm long, acute, ciliate. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Standard</emphasis>
15-18 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
11-17 mm, suborbicular, bright lemon or golden yellow, nectar guide yellow, back of standard sparsely pubescent, apex retuse, callosities of boss type. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Wing petals</emphasis>
12-14 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-5 mm, glabrous, subequal to the keel, each semi-pandurate, slightly curved upwards at the apex; completely free from the keel, apex obtuse, basal claw 2-3 mm long. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Keel petals</emphasis>
11-13 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
4-5 mm, glabrous, united into a falcate, navicular cup, apex obtuse, basal claw 3-4 mm long. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Stamens</emphasis>
diadelphous, nine fused together, the vexillary one free, all curved upwards at apex. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="49" pageNumber="50">Ovary</emphasis>
sparsely pubescent, style glabrous, 2-3 mm long 
<pageBreakToken pageId="50" pageNumber="51" start="start">curved</pageBreakToken>
upwards at apex, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">stigma</emphasis>
punctate. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Pods</emphasis>
19-30 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
2-2.5 cm, flat, linear, or obovate, dehiscent, surface shortly hirsute, smooth, brown and hard when dry, subseptate. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Seeds</emphasis>
2-3, flattened-orbicular, 17 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
17 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
10 mm, hilum central, elliptic 2-3 
<normalizedToken originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1 mm.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="50" pageNumber="51">named after the Serawai river in west Kalimantan, a tributary of the Kapuas river, where the species was first discovered.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
